 transitional phase in the history of the Raj, witnessing the impact of the First World War, major constitutional reform initiatives, the tragedy of the Amritsar massacre, and the launching of Gandhi’s mass movement. Asserts that the War was a watershed in official media manipulation and in the aftermath of the conflict the Government’s previously informal and ad hoc attempts to shape press reporting were placed on a more formal basis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aAmritsar massacre.  aBritish public.  aEmpire Press Union.  aFirst World War.  aFleet Street.  aGandhi's mass movement.  aIndian affairs.  aIndian empire.  aIndian politics.  aIndian press.  aIndian-run newspapers.  aMinto-Morley partnership.  aReuters.  aThe Times.  aconstitutional reform initiatives.  adomestic politics.  aimperial control.  apolitical elite.  apress coverage.1 aKaul, Chandrika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611976640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119766423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119766/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles